Project: PCA and tSNE¶

Marks: 30¶

Welcome to the project on PCA and tSNE. In this project. We will be using the auto-mpg dataset.

Objective:¶

The objective of this problem is to explore the data and reduce the number of features by using dimensionality reduction techniques like PCA and TSNE and generate meaningful insights.

Dataset:¶

There are 8 variables in the data:

  • mpg: miles per gallon
  • cyl: number of cylinders
  • disp: engine displacement (cu. inches) or engine size
  • hp: horsepower
  • wt: vehicle weight (lbs.)
  • acc: time taken to accelerate from O to 60 mph (sec.)
  • yr: model year
  • car name: car model name

Principal Component Analysis¶

Question 3:¶

  • Apply the PCA algorithm with number of components equal to the total number of columns in the data with random_state=1 (2 Marks)
  • Write observations on the variance explained by components (2 Marks)
In [18]:
#Defining the number of principal components to generate 
n=data_scaled.shape[1]

#Finding principal components for the data
pca = PCA(n_components=n, random_state=1)#Apply the PCA algorithm with random state = 1
data_pca1 = pd.DataFrame(pca.fit_transform(data_scaled)) #Fit and transform the pca function on scaled data

#The percentage of variance explained by each principal component
exp_var = pca.explained_variance_ratio_
In [19]:
# visualize the explained variance by individual components
plt.figure(figsize = (10,10))
plt.plot(range(1,8), exp_var.cumsum(), marker = 'o', linestyle = '--')
plt.title("Explained Variances by Components")
plt.xlabel("Number of Components")
plt.ylabel("Cumulative Explained Variance")
Out[19]:
Text(0, 0.5, 'Cumulative Explained Variance')
In [20]:
# find the least number of components that can explain more than 90% variance
sum = 0
for ix, i in enumerate(exp_var):
  sum = sum + i
  if(sum>0.90):
    print("Number of PCs that explain at least 90% variance: ", ix+1)
    break

Number of PCs that explain at least 90% variance:  3

Observations:

  • If we apply PCA with number of components=number of columns and random state=1, we can explain 90% of the variance with 3 Principal Components.
  • As we know, if we maximize this variance, we can explain the data set with less dimensions while losing the least amount of information.
  • Because of this 90% variance is very good, specially since we will only need 3 PCs.
  • 2 PCs only explain less than 85%, while 1 explains less than 75% variance. 4 principal components manages to explain over 95%, so that is also a good amount of variance explained.
  • However, 3 PCs seems to be a good sweet spot between variance explained and simplicity.

Question 4: Interpret the coefficients of three principal components from the below dataframe (6 Marks)¶

  PC1 PC2 PC3
mpg -0.400000 -0.210000 -0.260000
cylinders 0.420000 -0.190000 0.140000
displacement 0.430000 -0.180000 0.100000
horsepower 0.420000 -0.090000 -0.170000
weight 0.410000 -0.220000 0.280000
acceleration -0.280000 0.020000 0.890000
model year -0.230000 -0.910000 -0.020000

Observations:

  • Principal component one heavily weights positively cylinders, displacement, horsepower and weight. Meanwhile, it has negative consideration for MPG, acceleration and model year. This means that PC1 is explained by a positive sum of the blue values in that column, with the negative adition of mpg, acceleration and model year. In this PC, most of the values (bar acceleration and model year) seem to be pretty evenly weighted (whether positively or negatively).
  • We could explain PC1 as a linear combination: $$PC1=(-0.4*mpg)+(0.42*cylinders)+(0.43*displacement)+(0.42*horsepower)+(0.41*weight)+(-0.28*acceleration)+(-0.23*year)$$ As we can see, most values hold a similar contribution.
  • PC2 is a linear combination which heavily weights model year negatively (-0.91). This dimension seems to have the most importance by far out of any other for this PC. Every dimension seems to have a negative relation with it, aside from acceleration that will barely be considered in the linear combination (as it will be multiplied by 0.02).
  • We could explain PC2 as a linear combination: $$PC2=(-0.21*mpg)+(-0.19*cylinders)+(-0.18*displacement)+(-0.09*horsepower)+(-0.22*weight)+(-0.02*acceleration)+(-0.91*year)$$ As we can see, Year has a bigger contribution than any other column, while acceleration's (and to a lesser extent, horspower's) value will get attenuated substantially.
  • PC3 is a linear combination which heavily weights acceleration. This value will get multiplied by 0.89, which means it won't get attenuated much and hold a lot of weight, specially compared to the other values which all get multiplied with at most +/- 0.28. Here, there are 3 dimensions with a negative relation to the PC (MPG, horsepower and model year), while every other is positive.
  • We could explain PC3 as a linear combination: $$PC3=(-0.26*mpg)+(0.14*cylinders)+(0.10*displacement)+(-0.17*horsepower)+(0.28*weight)+(0.89*acceleration)+(-0.02*year)$$ As we can see, Acceleration has a bigger contribution than any other column, while year's value will get attenuated substantially.
  • While PC2 heavily weighted model year and attenuated acceleration, it seems that PC3 heavily weighted acceleration and attenuated model year.

# Let's assign points to 3 different groups
def grouping(x):
    first_component = x['Component 1']
    second_component = x['Component 2']
    if (first_component> 0) and (second_component >0): 
        return 'group_1'
    if (first_component >-20 ) and (first_component < 5):
        return 'group_2'
    else: 
        return 'group_3'
In [38]:
data_tsne['groups'] = data_tsne.apply(grouping,axis=1)

Group 2 is in between, with a lot of outliers in higher values and a few in lower. This group seems to include a lot of cars that didn't make Group 3 despite haver a high mpg value.
